agentInventoryMachineType.name: agentInventoryMachineType
agentInventoryMachineType.description: Type of the Machine used in the Switch

agentInventoryAdditionalPackages.name: agentInventoryAdditionalPackages
agentInventoryAdditionalPackages.description: Lists additional functional packages available on this unit.

agentInventorySoftwareVersion.name: agentInventorySoftwareVersion
agentInventorySoftwareVersion.description: Lists the version of software loaded on this unit.

agentTrapLogTotal.name: agentTrapLogTotal
agentTrapLogTotal.description: The total number of traps sent since last reset.

agentTrapLogTotalSinceLastViewed.name: agentTrapLogTotalSinceLastViewed
agentTrapLogTotalSinceLastViewed.description: The number of traps sent since last viewed.

agentTrapLogSystemTime.name: agentTrapLogSystemTime
agentTrapLogSystemTime.description: System uptime when trap was sent. This entry shows how long the system has been up when the trap occurred.

agentSupportedMibIndex.name: agentSupportedMibIndex
agentSupportedMibIndex.description: Unique index of the Supported MIB entry

agentSupportedMibName.name: agentSupportedMibName
agentSupportedMibName.description: The name of the MIB (RFC or IEEE) that is supported.

agentSupportedMibDescription.name: agentSupportedMibDescription
agentSupportedMibDescription.description: Description of the MIB (RFC or IEEE) that is supported.

agentLoginSessionTable.name: agentLoginSessionTable
agentLoginSessionTable.description: A table of the switch's login session

agentLoginSessionIndex.name: agentLoginSessionIndex
agentLoginSessionIndex.description: Agent Login Session Index of the switch

agentLoginSessionUserName.name: agentLoginSessionUserName
agentLoginSessionUserName.description: Agent Login Session UserName of the switch

agentLoginSessionIPAddress.name: agentLoginSessionIPAddress
agentLoginSessionIPAddress.description: Agent Login Session IP Address of the switch

agentLoginSessionConnectionType.name: agentLoginSessionConnectionType
agentLoginSessionConnectionType.description: Agent Login Session Connection Type of the switch

agentLoginSessionIdleTime.name: agentLoginSessionIdleTime
agentLoginSessionIdleTime.description: Agent Login Session Idle Time of the switch

agentLoginSessionSessionTime.name: agentLoginSessionSessionTime
agentLoginSessionSessionTime.description: Agent Login Session Time of the switch

agentLoginSessionStatus.name: agentLoginSessionStatus
agentLoginSessionStatus.description: Status of the user. active(1) - This connection is active. destroy(6) - Set to this value to disconnect this user.

agentTelnetLoginTimeout.name: agentTelnetLoginTimeout
agentTelnetLoginTimeout.description: Telnet login timeout (minutes) Config telnet timeout will set the telnet session timeout value. A session is active as long as the session has not remained idle for the value set. Specify a value from 0 to 160. A value of 0 indicates that a Telnet session remains active indefinitely. Note: Changing the timeout value for active sessions does not become effective until the session is reaccessed. Any keystroke will also activate the new timeout duration.

agentTelnetMaxSessions.name: agentTelnetMaxSessions
agentTelnetMaxSessions.description: Maximum number of Telnet Sessions Config telnet maxsessions is an integer value from 0 to 5 that specifies the maximum number of telnet sessions that can be established. If the value is 0, no Telnet session can be established.

agentTelnetAllowNewMode.name: agentTelnetAllowNewMode
agentTelnetAllowNewMode.description: Allow new telnet sessions (enable or disable) Config telnet disable means that no new Telnet sessions are to be established. Any already established session remains active until the session is ended or an abnormal network error ends it.

agentUserConfigCreate.name: agentUserConfigCreate
agentUserConfigCreate.description: Create a new user. When set with a non-empty string, a new user with that name will be created. This object will only return an empty string. This string is limited to alpha-numeric strings (uncluding the '-' and '_' characters).

agentUserName.name: agentUserName
agentUserName.description: Agent User Name. This string is limited to alpha-numeric strings (including the '-' and '_' characters).

agentUserPassword.name: agentUserPassword
agentUserPassword.description: Agent User Password This object will return an empty string even if a password is set.

agentUserStatus.name: agentUserStatus
agentUserStatus.description: Agent User Status. active(1) - This user account is active. destroy(6) - Set to this value to remove this user account.

agentUserAuthenticationType.name: agentUserAuthenticationType
agentUserAuthenticationType.description: SNMPv3 User Authentication. The user passsword must be set to a string greater than or equal to 8 characters for this to be set to anything but none(1). none(1) - no authentication used hmacmd5(1) - Use HMAC-MD5 authentication hmacsha(1) - Use HMAC-SHA authentication

agentUserEncryptionType.name: agentUserEncryptionType
agentUserEncryptionType.description: SNMPv3 User Encryption Can not be set to des(2) if agentUserAuthenticationType is set to none(1). none(1) - no encryption used des(2) - DES encryption used

agentUserEncryptionPassword.name: agentUserEncryptionPassword
agentUserEncryptionPassword.description: SNMPv3 User Encryption Password This object will return an empty string even if a password is set. agentUserEncryptionType must be set to des(2) before this object can be configured. This object will return an empty string even if a password is set.

agentSerialTimeout.name: agentSerialTimeout
agentSerialTimeout.description: agentSerialTimeout specifies the maximum connect time(in minutes) without console activity. A value of 0 indicates that a console can be connected indefinitely. The time range is 0 to 160.

agentSerialBaudrate.name: agentSerialBaudrate
agentSerialBaudrate.description: agentSerialBaudrate specifies the current baud rate at which the serial port will try to connect. The available values are 1200, 2400, 4800, 9600, 19200, 38400,57600, and 115200 baud.

agentSerialCharacterSize.name: agentSerialCharacterSize
agentSerialCharacterSize.description: agentSerialCharacterSize specifies the number of bits in a character. The number of bits is always 8.

agentSerialHWFlowControlMode.name: agentSerialHWFlowControlMode
agentSerialHWFlowControlMode.description: agentSerialHardwareFlowControl specifies whether hardware flow-control is enabled or disabled. Hardware Flow Control is always disabled.

agentSerialStopBits.name: agentSerialStopBits
agentSerialStopBits.description: agentSerialStopBits specifies the number of Stop bits per character. The number of Stop bits is always 1.

agentSerialParityType.name: agentSerialParityType
agentSerialParityType.description: agentSerialParityType specifies the Parity Method used on the Serial Port. The Parity Method is always None.

agentLagConfigCreate.name: agentLagConfigCreate
agentLagConfigCreate.description: Agent LAG Create. When this object is set with a non-empty string, a new LAG will be created if possible with the entered string as its name.

agentLagSummaryConfigTable.name: agentLagSummaryConfigTable
agentLagSummaryConfigTable.description: A summary table of the switch's LAG config entries

agentLagSummaryLagIndex.name: agentLagSummaryLagIndex
agentLagSummaryLagIndex.description: Agent LAG IfIndex. This value corresponds with the LAG interface in the ifTable.

agentLagSummaryName.name: agentLagSummaryName
agentLagSummaryName.description: Agent LAG Name. The associated name of the LAG used during creation.

agentLagSummaryLinkTrap.name: agentLagSummaryLinkTrap
agentLagSummaryLinkTrap.description: Agent LAG LinkTrap. Configures sending Link Up/Down traps when the LAG interface goes Up or Down.

agentLagSummaryAdminMode.name: agentLagSummaryAdminMode
agentLagSummaryAdminMode.description: Agent LAG AdminMode. Administratively enables or disables this LAG interface.

agentLagSummaryStpMode.name: agentLagSummaryStpMode
agentLagSummaryStpMode.description: Agent LAG StpMode If Dot1d is enabled, the valid values are: dot1d(1), fast(2), and off(3) If Dot1s is enabled, the valid values are: off(3) and dot1s(4)

agentLagSummaryAddPort.name: agentLagSummaryAddPort
agentLagSummaryAddPort.description: Agent LAG AddPort. Set to a non 0 value to add a port to the LAG. Values correspond to ifIndex values in the ifTable. Note: agentPortType for the port to be added must be full duplex and the same speed as previously added port(s), if any.

agentLagSummaryDeletePort.name: agentLagSummaryDeletePort
agentLagSummaryDeletePort.description: Agent LAG DeletePort. Set to a non 0 value to remove a port from the LAG. Values correspond to ifIndex values in the ifTable.

agentLagSummaryStatus.name: agentLagSummaryStatus
agentLagSummaryStatus.description: Agent LAG Status. active(1) - This LAG is enabled. destroy(6) - Set to this value to remove the LAG.

agentLagSummaryType.name: agentLagSummaryType
agentLagSummaryType.description: Agent LAG Type. static(1) - This LAG is staticly maintained. dynamic(2) - This LAG is dynamicly maintained.

agentLagDetailedConfigTable.name: agentLagDetailedConfigTable
agentLagDetailedConfigTable.description: A detailed table of the switch's LAG config entries

agentLagDetailedPortSpeed.name: agentLagDetailedPortSpeed
agentLagDetailedPortSpeed.description: LAG port speed. See agentPortType for a description and list of valid values.

agentLagDetailedPortStatus.name: agentLagDetailedPortStatus
agentLagDetailedPortStatus.description: LAG port status. active(1) - Actively participating in the LAG. inactive(2) - Not participating in the LAG.

agentLagConfigStaticCapability.name: agentLagConfigStaticCapability
agentLagConfigStaticCapability.description: Agent LAG Static Capability. Configures whether Static LAGs are supported on this device.

agentNetworkBurnedInMacAddress.name: agentNetworkBurnedInMacAddress
agentNetworkBurnedInMacAddress.description: The switch's network Burned-In MAC address

agentNetworkWebMode.name: agentNetworkWebMode
agentNetworkWebMode.description: The switch's network config protocol on next bootup

agentNetworkJavaMode.name: agentNetworkJavaMode
agentNetworkJavaMode.description: Configures the use of the Java interface through the Web.

agentNetworkMgmtVlan.name: agentNetworkMgmtVlan
agentNetworkMgmtVlan.description: The VLAN ID through which the switch can be managed using the agentNetworkIPAddress

agentServicePortBurnedInMacAddress.name: agentServicePortBurnedInMacAddress
agentServicePortBurnedInMacAddress.description: The switch's ServicePort Burned-In MAC address

agentSnmpCommunityCreate.name: agentSnmpCommunityCreate
agentSnmpCommunityCreate.description: Creates a new SNMP Community entry. Defaults: IPAddress 0.0.0.0 IpMask 0.0.0.0 AccessMode read-only Status config

agentSnmpCommunityConfigTable.name: agentSnmpCommunityConfigTable
agentSnmpCommunityConfigTable.description: A table of the switch's SNMP Config entries

agentSnmpCommunityName.name: agentSnmpCommunityName
agentSnmpCommunityName.description: The switch's Snmp Community Name This name identifies each SNMP community; the name can be up to 16 characters, and it is case-sensitive. Community names in the SNMP community must be unique. If you make multiple entries using the same community name, the first entry is kept and processed and all duplicate entries are ignored.

agentSnmpCommunityIPAddress.name: agentSnmpCommunityIPAddress
agentSnmpCommunityIPAddress.description: The switch's Snmp Community IP Address Client IP Address - This attribute is an IP address (or portion thereof) from which this device will accept SNMP packets with the associated community. The requesting entity's IP address is logical-ANDed with the Client IP Mask and the result must match the Client IP Address. Note: If the Client IP Mask is set to 0.0.0.0, a Client IP Address of 0.0.0.0 matches all IP addresses.

agentSnmpCommunityIPMask.name: agentSnmpCommunityIPMask
agentSnmpCommunityIPMask.description: The switch's Snmp Community IP Mask Client IP Mask - This attribute is a mask to be logical-ANDed with the requesting entity's IP address before comparison with the Client IP Address. If the result matches with Client IP Address then the address is an authenticated IP address. For example, if the Client IP Address is 9.47.128.0 and the corresponding Client IP Mask is 255.255.255.0, a range of incoming IP addresses would match, that is, the incoming IP addresses could be a value in the following range: 9.47.128.0 to 9.47.128.255. To have a specific IP address be the only authenticated IP address, set the Client IP Address to the required IP address and set the Client IP Mask to 255.255.255.255.

agentSnmpCommunityAccessMode.name: agentSnmpCommunityAccessMode
agentSnmpCommunityAccessMode.description: The switch's Snmp Community Access Mode Access Mode - This value can be read-only or read/write. A community with a read-only access allows for switch information to be displayed. A community with a read/write access allows for configuration changes to be made and for information to be displayed.

agentSnmpCommunityStatus.name: agentSnmpCommunityStatus
agentSnmpCommunityStatus.description: The switch's Snmp Community Status. active(1) - This community is active, allowing SNMP managers associated with this community to manage the switch according to its access right. notInService(2) - This community is not active; no SNMP requests using this community will be accepted. In this case the SNMP manager associated with this community cannot manage the switch until the Status is changed back to active(1). config(3) - The community Status must be set to this value in order to configure it. When creating a new community entry, initial Status will be set to this value. destroy(4) - Set to this value to remove the community from the agent.

agentSnmpTrapReceiverCreate.name: agentSnmpTrapReceiverCreate
agentSnmpTrapReceiverCreate.description: Creates a new trap receiver entry. Defaults: IPAddress 0.0.0.0 status config

agentSnmpTrapReceiverConfigTable.name: agentSnmpTrapReceiverConfigTable
agentSnmpTrapReceiverConfigTable.description: Trap messages are sent across a network to an SNMP Network Manager. These messages alert the manager to events occurring within the switch or on the network. Up to six simultaneous trap receivers are supported.

agentSnmpTrapReceiverConfigEntry.name: agentSnmpTrapReceiverConfigEntry
agentSnmpTrapReceiverConfigEntry.description: Switch's Snmp Trace Receiver Config entry

agentSnmpTrapReceiverIndex.name: agentSnmpTrapReceiverIndex
agentSnmpTrapReceiverIndex.description: The switch's Snmp Trap Receiver Index

agentSnmpTrapReceiverCommunityName.name: agentSnmpTrapReceiverCommunityName
agentSnmpTrapReceiverCommunityName.description: The switch's Snmp Trap Receiver Community Name. This is the SNMP community name of the remote network manager; the name can be up to 16 characters, and is case-sensitive.

agentSnmpTrapReceiverIPAddress.name: agentSnmpTrapReceiverIPAddress
agentSnmpTrapReceiverIPAddress.description: IP Address - Each IP address parameter is four integer numbers. The numbers range from 0 to 255.

agentSnmpTrapReceiverStatus.name: agentSnmpTrapReceiverStatus
agentSnmpTrapReceiverStatus.description: The switch's Snmp Trap Reciever Status. active(1) - This trap receiver is active, allowing SNMP Traps to be sent to this receiver. notInService(2) - This trap reciever is not active; no SNMP Traps will be sent to this reciever until it's set back to active(1). config(3) - The trap reciever Status must be set to this value in order to configure it. When creating a new trap receiver entry, the Status will initially be set to this value. Note: agentSnmpTrapReceiverIPAddress must be set to non-zero before changing to active(1) or notInService(2). destroy(4) - Set to this value to remove the trap receiver entry from the agent.

agentSnmpLinkUpDownTrapFlag.name: agentSnmpLinkUpDownTrapFlag
agentSnmpLinkUpDownTrapFlag.description: Link Up/Down Flag - Enable/Disable Link Up/Link Down traps for the entire switch. When set to Enable, the Link Up/Down traps will be sent only if the Link Trap flag setting associated with the port (Port Configuration Menu) is set to Enable.

agentSnmpMultipleUsersTrapFlag.name: agentSnmpMultipleUsersTrapFlag
agentSnmpMultipleUsersTrapFlag.description: Multiple Users Flag - Enable/Disable Multiple User traps. When the value is set to Enable, a Multiple User Trap is sent whenever someone logs in to the terminal interface (EIA 232 or Telnet) and there is already an existing terminal interface session.

agentSnmpSpanningTreeTrapFlag.name: agentSnmpSpanningTreeTrapFlag
agentSnmpSpanningTreeTrapFlag.description: Spanning Tree Flag - This flag enables the sending of new root traps and topology change notification traps.

agentSnmpBroadcastStormTrapFlag.name: agentSnmpBroadcastStormTrapFlag
agentSnmpBroadcastStormTrapFlag.description: Broadcast Storm Flag - This flag enables or disables the broadcast storm trap. You must also enable Broadcast Storm Recovery Mode (see the Switch Configuration Menu). When this value is set to Enable and Broadcast Storm Recovery mode is set to Enable, the Broadcast Storm Start/End traps are sent when the switch enters and leaves Broadcast Storm Recovery.

agentSpanningTreeMode.name: agentSpanningTreeMode
agentSpanningTreeMode.description: The switch's Spanning Tree Switch Status

agentSwitchAddressAgingTimeoutTable.name: agentSwitchAddressAgingTimeoutTable
agentSwitchAddressAgingTimeoutTable.description: The switch's address aging timeout table

agentSwitchAddressAgingTimeoutEntry.name: agentSwitchAddressAgingTimeoutEntry
agentSwitchAddressAgingTimeoutEntry.description: Aging information about a specific Filtering Database.

agentSwitchAddressAgingTimeout.name: agentSwitchAddressAgingTimeout
agentSwitchAddressAgingTimeout.description: The FDB entry's address aging timeout (in seconds)

agentSwitchBroadcastControlMode.name: agentSwitchBroadcastControlMode
agentSwitchBroadcastControlMode.description: The switch config broadcast allows you to enable or disable broadcast storm recovery mode. When you specify Enable for Broadcast Storm Recovery and the broadcast traffic on any Ethernet port exceeds 20 percent of the link speed, the switch blocks (discards) the broadcast traffic until the broadcast traffic returns to 10 percent or less. Upper limit for 10M link is 20% and lower limit is 10%. For 100M link Upper limit is 5% and lower limit is 2%

agentSwitchDot3FlowControlMode.name: agentSwitchDot3FlowControlMode
agentSwitchDot3FlowControlMode.description: Config switchconfig flowcontrol allows you to enable or disable 802.3x flow control for the switch. This value applies to only full-duplex mode ports.

agentSwitchIGMPSnoopingAdminMode.name: agentSwitchIGMPSnoopingAdminMode
agentSwitchIGMPSnoopingAdminMode.description: This enables or disables IGMP Snooping on the system.

agentSwitchIGMPSnoopingGroupMembershipIn.name: agentSwitchIGMPSnoopingGroupMembershipInterval
agentSwitchIGMPSnoopingGroupMembershipIn.description: The amount of time in seconds a switch will wait for a report for a particular group on a particular interface before it deletes the interface from the entry.

agentSwitchIGMPSnoopingMaxResponseTime.name: agentSwitchIGMPSnoopingMaxResponseTime
agentSwitchIGMPSnoopingMaxResponseTime.description: The amount of time in seconds a switch will wait after sending a query on an interface because it did not receive a report for a particular group in that interface. This value must be less than agentSwitchIGMPSnoopingQueryInterval.

agentSwitchIGMPSnoopingMRPExpirationTime.name: agentSwitchIGMPSnoopingMRPExpirationTime
agentSwitchIGMPSnoopingMRPExpirationTime.description: Multicast Router Present Expiration Time. The amount of time in seconds a switch will wait for a query to be received on an interface before the interface is removed from the list of interfaces with mutlticast routers attached. A value of zero indicates an infinite timeout, i.e. the entries in the list will not expire.

agentSwitchIGMPSnoopingPortMask.name: agentSwitchIGMPSnoopingPortMask
agentSwitchIGMPSnoopingPortMask.description: IGMP Snooping Port Mask. This allows configuration of IGMP Snooping on selected ports. IGMP Snooping cannot be enabled on an interface that has routing enabled, or is a member of a LAG. If a port which has IGMP Snooping enabled becomes enabled for routing, or is enlisted as a member of a LAG, IGMP Snooping functionality will be disabled on that port. IGMP Snooping functionality will be subsequently be reenabled if routing is disabled or LAG membership is removed from an interface that had previously had IGMP Snooping enabled. To obtain port numbers from interface numbers, use the objects agentPortDot1dBasePort and agentPortIfIndex in the agentPortConfigTable table.

agentSwitchIGMPSnoopingMulticastControlF.name: agentSwitchIGMPSnoopingMulticastControlFramesProcessed
agentSwitchIGMPSnoopingMulticastControlF.description: Multicast Control Frames Processed by CPU. The number of multicast control frames that have been processed by the CPU.

agentSwitchMFDBEntry.name: agentSwitchMFDBEntry
agentSwitchMFDBEntry.description: Contains Forwarding and Filtering information per Vlan Index, MAC Address, and Component User.

agentSwitchMFDBVlanId.name: agentSwitchMFDBVlanId
agentSwitchMFDBVlanId.description: Vlan Index for which this entry is associated with.

agentSwitchMFDBMacAddress.name: agentSwitchMFDBMacAddress
agentSwitchMFDBMacAddress.description: A multicast MAC address for which the switch has forwarding and or filtering information.

agentSwitchMFDBProtocolType.name: agentSwitchMFDBProtocolType
agentSwitchMFDBProtocolType.description: The component that is responsible for this entry in the Multicast Forwarding Database.

agentSwitchMFDBType.name: agentSwitchMFDBType
agentSwitchMFDBType.description: This displays the type of the entry. static(1) - Entries configured by the end user dynamic(2) - Entries added as a result of a learning process or protocol

agentSwitchMFDBDescription.name: agentSwitchMFDBDescription
agentSwitchMFDBDescription.description: Text description of this multicast table entry.

agentSwitchMFDBForwardingPortMask.name: agentSwitchMFDBForwardingPortMask
agentSwitchMFDBForwardingPortMask.description: BitMask indicating which ports this entry indicates should be forwarded. To obtain port numbers from interface numbers, use the objects agentPortDot1dBasePort and agentPortIfIndex in the agentPortConfigTable table.

agentSwitchMFDBFilteringPortMask.name: agentSwitchMFDBFilteringPortMask
agentSwitchMFDBFilteringPortMask.description: BitMask indicating which ports this entry indicates should be filtered. To obtain port numbers from interface numbers, use the objects agentPortDot1dBasePort and agentPortIfIndex in the agentPortConfigTable table.

agentSwitchMFDBSummaryTable.name: agentSwitchMFDBSummaryTable
agentSwitchMFDBSummaryTable.description: The Multicast Forwarding Database Summary table

agentSwitchMFDBSummaryEntry.name: agentSwitchMFDBSummaryEntry
agentSwitchMFDBSummaryEntry.description: Summarizes the forwarding ports for all components registered for all MFDB table entries with the same Vlan Index and MAC Address.

agentSwitchMFDBSummaryVlanId.name: agentSwitchMFDBSummaryVlanId
agentSwitchMFDBSummaryVlanId.description: Vlan Index for which this entry is associated with.

agentSwitchMFDBSummaryMacAddress.name: agentSwitchMFDBSummaryMacAddress
agentSwitchMFDBSummaryMacAddress.description: A multicast MAC address for which the switch has forwarding and or filtering information.

agentSwitchMFDBSummaryForwardingPortMask.name: agentSwitchMFDBSummaryForwardingPortMask
agentSwitchMFDBSummaryForwardingPortMask.description: Port Mask indicating which ports this entry indicates should be forwarded. To obtain port numbers from interface numbers, use the objects agentPortDot1dBasePort and agentPortIfIndex in the agentPortConfigTable table.

agentSwitchMFDBMaxTableEntries.name: agentSwitchMFDBMaxTableEntries
agentSwitchMFDBMaxTableEntries.description: This displays the maximum number of entries that can possibly be in the Multicast Forwarding Database table.

agentSwitchMFDBMostEntriesUsed.name: agentSwitchMFDBMostEntriesUsed
agentSwitchMFDBMostEntriesUsed.description: This displays the largest number of entries that have been present in the Multicast Forwarding Database table. This value is also known as the MFDB high-water mark.

agentSwitchMFDBCurrentEntries.name: agentSwitchMFDBCurrentEntries
agentSwitchMFDBCurrentEntries.description: This displays the current number of entries in the Multicast Forwarding Database table.

agentTransferUploadMode.name: agentTransferUploadMode
agentTransferUploadMode.description: Transfer upload mode configures the mode to use when uploading from the switch. The mode is either X/Y/ZMODEM or TFTP. X/Y/ZMODEM is valid only when the file transfer is initiated by the serial EIA 232 port.

agentTransferUploadServerIP.name: agentTransferUploadServerIP
agentTransferUploadServerIP.description: Transfer upload tftpserverip configures the IP address of the server where the file is located. It is valid only when the Transfer Mode is TFTP. The address is 4 integer bytes ranging from 0 to 255.

agentTransferUploadPath.name: agentTransferUploadPath
agentTransferUploadPath.description: Transfer upload tftppath configures the directory path where the file is to be uploaded to. The switch remembers the last file path used.

agentTransferUploadFilename.name: agentTransferUploadFilename
agentTransferUploadFilename.description: Transfer upload tftpfilename configures the file name for the file being uploaded from the switch. It can be up to 32 alphanumeric characters. The switch remembers the last file name used. File path can be appended to the file name if the string is less than 17 characters. Otherwise, the File Path field will need to be used and the File Name will be appended to the File Path as is. An example would be File Path set to c:\tftp\code\ and File Name set to e1r1v1.opr. Note: File Name, File Path, and TFTP Server IP Address are applicable only if the Transfer Mode is TFTP.

agentTransferUploadDataType.name: agentTransferUploadDataType
agentTransferUploadDataType.description: Transfer upload datatype configures the type of file to upload from the switch. The types for upload are: - Configuration File - Error log - Message log - Trap log

agentTransferUploadStart.name: agentTransferUploadStart
agentTransferUploadStart.description: Transfer upload start will start an upload transfer. The agentTransferUploadMode object must not be set to xmodem(2), ymodem(3), or zmodem(4) to initiate a transfer via SNMP.

agentTransferUploadStatus.name: agentTransferUploadStatus
agentTransferUploadStatus.description: Indicates the current status of an upload transfer.

agentTransferDownloadMode.name: agentTransferDownloadMode
agentTransferDownloadMode.description: Transfer download mode configures the mode to use when downloading to the switch. The mode is either X/Y/ZMODEM or TFTP. X/Y/ZMODEM is valid only when the file transfer is initiated by the serial EIA 232 port.

agentTransferDownloadServerIP.name: agentTransferDownloadServerIP
agentTransferDownloadServerIP.description: Transfer download tftpserverip configures the IP address of the server where the file is located. It is valid only when the Transfer Mode is TFTP. The address is 4 integer bytes ranging from 0 to 255.

agentTransferDownloadPath.name: agentTransferDownloadPath
agentTransferDownloadPath.description: Transfer download tftppath configures the directory path where the file is located. The switch remembers the last file path used.

agentTransferDownloadFilename.name: agentTransferDownloadFilename
agentTransferDownloadFilename.description: Transfer download tftpfilename configures the file name for the file being downloaded to the switch. It can be up to 32 alphanumeric characters. The switch remembers the last file name used. File path can be appended to the file name if the string is less than 33 characters. Otherwise, the File Path field will need to be used and the File Name will be appended to the File Path as is. An example would be File Path set to c:\tftp\code\ and File Name set to e1r1v1.opr. Note: File Name, File Path, and TFTP Server IP Address are applicable only if the Transfer Mode is TFTP.

agentTransferDownloadDataType.name: agentTransferDownloadDataType
agentTransferDownloadDataType.description: Transfer download datatype configures the type of file to download to the switch. The types for download are: code - Code File config - Configuration File sshkey-rsa1 - SSH-1 RSA Key File sshkey-rsa2 - SSH-2 RSA Key PEM File sshkey-dsa - SSH-2 DSA Key PEM File sslpem-root - SSL Trusted Root Certificate PEM File sslpem-server - SSL Server Certificate PEM File sslpem-dhweak - SSL DH Weak Encryption Parameter PEM File sslpem-dhstrong - SSL DH Strong Encryption Parameter PEM File Note: SSH Key files can only be downloaded if SSH Server is administratively disabled, and there are no active SSH sessions.

agentTransferDownloadStart.name: agentTransferDownloadStart
agentTransferDownloadStart.description: Transfer download start will start an download transfer. The agentTransferDownloadMode object must not be set to xmodem(2), ymodem(3), or zmodem(4) to initiate a transfer via SNMP.

agentTransferDownloadStatus.name: agentTransferDownloadStatus
agentTransferDownloadStatus.description: Indicates the current status of an download transfer.

agentPortMirroringMode.name: agentPortMirroringMode
agentPortMirroringMode.description: Port mirroring mode: enable - enable mirroring mode disable - disable mirroring mode delete - clear MirroredPort and Probe Port configuration

agentDot3adAggPortTable.name: agentDot3adAggPortTable
agentDot3adAggPortTable.description: This table provides 802.3ad link aggregation information for each physical port that is not available through the standard MIB.

agentDot3adAggPortEntry.name: agentDot3adAggPortEntry
agentDot3adAggPortEntry.description: Information about a table entry. The agentDot3adAggPort identifies the external interface number of the port.

agentPortConfigTable.name: agentPortConfigTable
agentPortConfigTable.description: A table of the switch's physical port config entries

agentPortDot1dBasePort.name: agentPortDot1dBasePort
agentPortDot1dBasePort.description: The port number of this port.

agentPortSTPMode.name: agentPortSTPMode
agentPortSTPMode.description: The switch's Port Spanning Tree Protocol Mode STP mode values are: dot1d (the default) fast, indicates you want to use the fast spanning tree mode off, indicates the STP mode is turned off for a particular port This object is only supported when the Dot1d Protocol is enabled.

agentPortSTPState.name: agentPortSTPState
agentPortSTPState.description: The switch's Port Spanning Tree Protocol State. This object is only supported when the Dot1d Protocol is enabled.

agentPortPhysicalMode.name: agentPortPhysicalMode
agentPortPhysicalMode.description: The switch's Port Speed Mode. This is the configured physical mode. This object is read-only for gigabit ports

agentPortPhysicalStatus.name: agentPortPhysicalStatus
agentPortPhysicalStatus.description: The switch's Port Physical Speed Status. This is the current actual speed.

agentPortLinkTrapMode.name: agentPortLinkTrapMode
agentPortLinkTrapMode.description: If enabled, link up and link down traps will be sent for this port.

agentPortClearStats.name: agentPortClearStats
agentPortClearStats.description: clear stats for this port only

agentPortDefaultType.name: agentPortDefaultType
agentPortDefaultType.description: This object identifies the default administrative port type, to be used in conjunction with the operational port type denoted by agentPortType. The set of possible values for this object is the same as the set defined for the agentPortType object. This object represents the administratively-configured type of the MAU. If auto-negotiation is not enabled or is not implemented for this MAU, the value of this object determines the operational type of the MAU. In this case, a set to this object will force the MAU into the specified operating mode. If auto-negotiation is implemented and enabled for this MAU, the operational type of the MAU is determined by auto-negotiation, and the value of this object denotes the type to which the MAU will automatically revert if/when auto-negotiation is later disabled. The valid values for this object are: dot3MauType10BaseTHD dot3MauType10BaseTFD dot3MauType100BaseTXHD dot3MauType100BaseTXFD dot3MauType100BaseFXFD dot3MauType1000BaseSXFD

agentPortType.name: agentPortType
agentPortType.description: This object identifies the port type. An initial set of MAU types are defined in RFC 2668. The assignment of OBJECT IDENTIFIERs to new types of MAUs is managed by the IANA. If the MAU type is unknown, the object identifier unknownMauType OBJECT IDENTIFIER ::= { 0 0 } is returned. Note that unknownMauType is a syntactically valid object identifier, and any conformant implementation of ASN.1 and the BER must be able to generate and recognize this value. This object represents the operational type of the MAU, as determined by either (1) the result of the auto-negotiation function or (2) if auto-negotiation is not enabled or is not implemented for this MAU, by the value of the object agentPortDefaultType, or (3) for the GigE card a value determined by the GBIC connected to the card. In case (2), a set to the object agentPortDefaultType will force the MAU into the new operating mode. The valid values for this object are: dot3MauType10BaseTHD dot3MauType10BaseTFD dot3MauType100BaseTXHD dot3MauType100BaseTXFD dot3MauType100BaseFXFD dot3MauType1000BaseSXFD dot3MauType1000BaseTFD
